When do investors choose risky options: private vs.Â public equity? A laboratory experiment.

Research question

  • the paper studies equity market participation in private and public markets.

hypotheses

  • exploration explains the difference between the active participation in private vs.Â public markets.

theoretical predictions

  • assume forecasting rules about future returns.

  • in strategy environments players

LMT paper, 2018

  • extrapolative expectations \(F^e\) \[ F^e_{t-k} x_{t+1} = E_{t-k} x_{t+1} + \gamma (x_{t-k}-E_{t-k-1} x_{t-k}) \]
  • sticky expectations \(F^s\)

\[ F^s_{t-k} x_{t+1} = (1-\lambda) E_{t-k} x_{t+1} + \lambda (F^s_{t-k-1} x_{t+1}) \] - combining both components, \[ F_{t-k} x_{t+1} - E_{t-k} x_{t+1} = \gamma (x_{t-k}-E_{t-k-1} x_{t-k}) + \lambda (F_{t-k-1} x_{t+1} - E_{t-k} x_{t+1}) \]

  • in non-recursive form, \[ F_{t} x_{t+1} = (1-\lambda)\sum^2_{k=0}\lambda^k E_{t-k} x_{t+1}+\gamma \sum^2_{k=0}\lambda^k (x_{t-k}-E_{t-k-1}x_{t-k}) \] The authors estimate using NLS and get that \(\lambda=0.13\) and \(\gamma=0.42\)
source("jarabe.R")
pay.out<-135
in.meanpay<-150
thres<-pay.out-in.meanpay
n<-200
rho<-.85
ser<-20
p1<-seq(n)
epsi<-rnorm(n)*ser
xini<-0
xse<-rep(NA,n)
xse[1]<-xini
for(i in seq(2,n)){
  xse[i] = rho*xse[i-1]  + epsi[i]
  }
xf<-fmt.o.forecast(xse,.13,rho,.42,2)
plot(xse+in.meanpay, type="l",lwd=2,ylim=c(0,300))
lines(c(NA,NA,NA,NA,xf+in.meanpay),col="red",lty=2)
abline(h=pay.out)

## We analyze whether player following FMT decides IN or OUT
state.in<-rep(NA,length(xse))
state.in[1:4]<-1
beliefs<-rep(NA,length(xse)) #this vector fills the missing values with the RE belief 
fmt.beliefs<-rep(NA,length(xse)) #this vector stores FMT beliefs
beliefs[1:4]<-xse[1:4]
fmt.beliefs[1:4]<-xse[1:4]
for(t in seq(4,(length(xse)-1))){
    if(state.in[t]==0){
      beliefs[t]<- rho*beliefs[t-1]}
    else
      {beliefs[t]<- xse[t]}
    xf_u<-fmt.u.forecast(beliefs[1:t],state.in[1:t],.13,rho,.42,2)
    fmt.beliefs[t]<-xf_u
    state.in[t+1]<-fmt.decision(xf_u, thres)
}
count.out<-sum(state.in==0)/n
count.out
[1] 0.35
plot(fmt.beliefs+in.meanpay, type="l",lwd=2,ylim=c(0,300))
lines(xse+in.meanpay, col="red")
abline(h=pay.out)
